1bh.title: Terminal versus instrumental goals / values / preferences
1bh.clickbait: Distinguish events wanted for their consequences, from events wanted locally.
1bh.text:
'Instrumental goals' or 'instrumental values' are things that an agent wants for the sake of achieving other things; for example, we might want to get into a car, not because we enjoy the act of opening car doors for their own sake, but because we want to drive somewhere else.  'Terminal' goals, values, or preferences are those where the preference is derived locally rather than by looking at further or distant consequences; if you enjoy eating chocolate (and otherwise approve of this enjoyment, etcetera) then you aren't deriving your preference based on what you believe to be the *further consequences* of eating chocolate.  That is, terminal value can be contributed by local evaluation of the causal graph of events, while instrumental value derives from the event's relation to other parts of the event graph.  On a moral or ethical level, instrumental values are justified by appealing to their consequences, while terminal values are justified without appeal to their consequences.

Further reading:

- http://lesswrong.com/lw/l4/terminal_values_and_instrumental_values/
- http://wiki.lesswrong.com/wiki/Terminal_value#Terminal_vs._instrumental_values
- http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intrinsic_value_(ethics) and http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instrumental_value
